'''Andrew Henry Robertson''' (born 11 March 1994) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left-back]] for {{English football updater|Liverpoo}} club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Captain (association football)|captains]] the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]. He will leave Liverpool on 30 June 2026, upon the expiry of his contract, and will join [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref name="Tottenham"/>

Robertson began his senior career in 2012 with one season at then-amateur [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]]. In his season at [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], he was runner up in the [[2013–14 Scottish Cup]]. He was named [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year]] and in the [[PFA Scotland Team of the Year]], before joining [[Premier League]] side [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] in July 2014 for a fee of £2.85&nbsp;million. Robertson was relegated, promoted and then relegated again in his three seasons at Hull City.

Robertson joined Liverpool in July 2017 for an undisclosed fee, believed to be an initial £8&nbsp;million. His honours with Liverpool include the [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League]], the [[2019–20 Premier League]], the [[2019 UEFA Super Cup]], the [[2019 FIFA Club World Cup]] and a 2021–22 season [[2021–22 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] and [[2021–22 FA Cup|FA Cup]] domestic double. The [[2022 FA Community Shield]] win meant he had won once each at that stage, the complete set of all seven first tier trophies available to Liverpool. He has since won a second [[EFL Cup]] ([[2023-24 EFL Cup|2024]]) and [[Premier League|Premier League title]] ([[2024–25 Premier League|2025]]) with Liverpool.

Robertson was named in the PFA Team of the Year in [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#Premier League 10|2018–19]] and [[PFA Team of the Year (2020s)#Winners|2019–20]]. His first [[UEFA]] individual award was inclusion in their 2018 Champions League breakthrough team. UEFA also named him in both their Champions League Squad of the Season and their [[UEFA Team of the Year#Team of the Year 2019|fans' Team of the Year]] in [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League|2019]]. He was again named in their Champions League Team of the Season for the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|2021–22]] season.

Robertson made his full Scotland debut in May 2014. He was appointed Scotland captain in September 2018, and has led his country at [[UEFA Euro 2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]]. With 92 caps, Robertson is the second-highest capped player to play for the Scotland men's national team,<ref name=sfaroll>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scotland/roll-of-honour/mens-roll-of-honour/|title=Scotland Men's International Roll of Honour &#124; Scottish FA|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref> and is also the highest-capped player while serving as Scotland captain. In November 2025, on his 90th cap, Robertson captained his country to a first [[FIFA World Cup]] since [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]] in a famous 4–2 victory against Denmark.<ref name="Canavan">{{cite news |last=Canavan |first=Amy |date=18 November 2025 |title=Scotland qualify for first men's World Cup in 28 years after Denmark epic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/ce8glxdnx9wt |work=BBC Sport Scotland |location=Glasgow, Scotland |publisher=BBC |access-date=19 November 2025}}</ref>

== Early life and career ==
Robertson was born in [[Glasgow]]<ref name=":0">{{cite news |last=Greig |first=Martin |date=29 May 2019 |title=Liverpool's Andy Robertson: The people & places behind Scotland defender's rise |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48413180 |access-date=30 May 2019 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> to parents Brian and Pauline.<ref name=recope>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/andy-robertson-opens-up-glittering-22340185|title=Andy Robertson on the mental toughness the star had passed down from his dad|first=Scott|last=McDermott|date=12 July 2020|website=Daily Record}}</ref> He has an elder brother named Stephen.<ref name=livfam>{{Cite web|url=https://legacy.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/337304-exclusive-interview-andy-robertson-liverpool|title=Big interview &#124; Family values making Andy Robertson a modest hero|date=11 February 2019|website=Liverpool FC}}</ref> He is of [[Irish Scottish people|Irish]] descent via his [[Glenfarne]]-born grandmother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzz.ie/sport/robertson-backstory-people-cheer-scotland-24299143|title=Robertson has the backstory that will get people to cheer Scotland in Euro 2020|first=Kieran|last=Cunningham|date=11 June 2021|website=Buzz.ie|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

Brian grew up on [[Maryhill]]'s [[Wyndford]] estate. A tenacious amateur player nicknamed "Pop" after [[Pop Robson]],<ref name=pop>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rousingthekop.com/2024/05/02/andy-robertson-wife-mbe-salary-height-net-worth/|title=Andy Robertson's life outside of football from wife to net worth|first=Kyle|last=Archer|date=2 May 2024|website=Rousing The Kop}}</ref> Brian was a childhood friend of footballers [[Jim Duffy (footballer)|Jim Duffy]] and [[Charlie Nicholas]].<ref name=":0" /> However a spinal injury required Brian to wear a back brace, preventing a sporting career.<ref name=":0" /> Robertson later said of Stephen as an amateur footballer, "He didn't move much, he was a bit of a static striker but scored a lot of goals."<ref name=livfam/>

Robertson attended [[St Ninian's High School, Giffnock|St Ninian's High School]] in [[Giffnock]], [[East Renfrewshire]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Scotland players' old schools send good luck messages {{!}} Tes Magazine |url=https://www.tes.com/magazine/archived/scotland-players-old-schools-send-good-luck-messages |date=11 June 2021 |access-date=27 December 2021 |work=TES}}</ref> from 2006 to 2012. There he captained the football team. He was also the junior captain of his local golf club in Glasgow.<ref>{{Cite web |last=McEwan |first=Michael |date=5 November 2021 |title=Andy Robertson: How a Glasgow golf club helped mould a football hero |url=https://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/andy-robertson-how-a-glasgow-golf-club-helped-mould-a-liverpool-hero/ |access-date=15 November 2021 |website=bunkered.co.uk |language=en-US}}</ref>

Robertson played for Giffnock Soccer Centre, and then joined the youth set up at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], the team he supported as a boy. Celtic Head of Youth, [[Chris McCart]], then released him<ref name=celmcc>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-andy-robertson-jurgen-klopp-13397200|title=From a Glasgow call centre to Anfield – the Andy Robertson story|first=James|last=Pearce|date=27 July 2017|website=Liverpool Echo}}</ref> aged 15 in 2009, considering him too small.<ref>{{cite web |date=7 December 2013 |title=Dundee United starlet Andy Roberston: Celtic made a small blunder the day they let me go |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/dundee-united-starlet-andy-roberston-2900858 |access-date=25 July 2014 |website=Daily Record}}</ref> That was despite John Gallagher who had coached Robertson at under-14 and under-15, lobbying for Robertson.<ref name=":0" />

== Club career ==
=== Queen's Park ===
Gallagher recommended Robertson to [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]], located conveniently for Robertson and his family in Glasgow's South side. In their youth setup he was nurtured by key figures such as head of youth David McCallum and technical director Andy McGlennan, who encouraged Robertson's switch to left-back from a more advanced position.<ref name=":0" />

Manager [[Gardner Speirs]] called Robertson up to the Queen's Park first team at the start of season [[2012–13 in Scottish football|2012–13]].<ref name=":2"/> On 28 July 2012, 18-year-old Robertson made his senior football debut. That was in Queen's Park's [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] penalty shoot out win at [[Berwick Rangers F.C.|Berwick Rangers]]. The match attendance was 372.<ref name=guachafin/><ref>{{cite news |date=28 July 2012 |title=Ramsdens Cup: Berwick Rangers 2–2 Queen's Park (aet, 2–3 pens) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/19027896 |access-date=11 June 2015 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He scored his first senior goal when losing 2–1 at home to [[East Stirlingshire F.C.|East Stirlingshire]] on 13 November 2012.<ref name=sb/>

Queen's Park were still an amateur club at the time, so players were only paid expenses. Robertson posted on social media in August 2012, "Life at this age is rubbish with no money. #needajob."<ref name=guachafin>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/may/21/andy-robertson-liverpool-real-madrid-interview-champions-league-final|title=Andy Robertson: 'The problem with Real Madrid is they're all fantastic'|first=Donald|last=McRae|work=The Guardian|date=21 May 2018}}</ref> As a part-time footballer, Robertson trained/played 3 evenings per week plus Saturday afternoons.<ref name=teleg>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/05/19/andrew-robertsons-remarkable-rise-celtic-reject-champions-league/|title=Andrew Robertson's remarkable rise from Celtic reject to a Champions League final|first=Roddy|last=Forsyth|work=The Telegraph|date=19 May 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Robertson did work as a telephone service recipient for ticket bookings at [[Hampden Park]] where Queen's Park were based.<ref name=wfiphone>{{Cite web|url=https://worldfootballindex.com/2020/11/the-journey-of-andy-robertson-from-queens-park-to-liverpool-bukowski-dont-try/|title=The Journey Of Andy Robertson: From Queen's Park To King Of The World|first=Mochammad Naufal|last=Rizki|date=22 November 2020}}</ref> At lunch time he used the gym facilities there to bulk up.<ref name=livfam/> He took a part-time Christmas job<ref name=teleg/> on the tills at [[Marks and Spencer]] on [[Sauchiehall Street]] in Glasgow.<ref name=guachafin/> He also did [[landscaping]] work.<ref name=tribune>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theplayerstribune.com/articles/andy-robertson-liverpool-champions-league|title=This Is for Liverpool|first=Andrew|last=Robertson|date=29 May 2019|website=The Players' Tribune}}</ref> He later commented on that season with Queen's Park, "I did apply for a couple of uni courses, but by the January or February of the season I knew at the end of the season there was going to be at least two options of full-time football. I knew I could put that (university) on the backburner and I was at least going to have a crack at it (professional football)." Robertson's career plan should he have followed his brother in studying at university, was to teach [[Physical Education|PE]].<ref name=livfam/>

[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] having gone into administration the season before, had been placed in the same division as Queen's Park that season; the lowest of Scotland's four men's senior football divisions. Robertson later commented, "we also played at a full [[Ibrox Park|Ibrox]] – 50,000 – and it was a great experience. We got beaten 2–0 but it was tight until the 87th minute. I missed a glorious chance which I'm always reminded of by old team-mates."<ref name=guachafin/>

Robertson made 43 appearances that season,<ref name="Soccerway"/> more than any other player in the squad.<ref name=":2"/> Queen's Park finished third in the [[2012–13 Scottish Third Division]], qualifying for the end of season play-offs. Queen's Park lost the home first leg 1–0 to a second-half stoppage time, [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]] penalty by [[Andy Rodgers]].<ref name=qppet>{{Cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/05/08/scotland/play-offs-34/queen-s-park/peterhead/1472265/|title=Queen's Park vs Peterhead live scores & match info &#124; Soccerway|website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref> [[Lawrence Shankland]] scored the 87th minute Queen's Park goal, losing the away leg 3–1.<ref name=petqp>{{Cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/05/11/scotland/play-offs-34/peterhead/queen-s-park/1472268/|title=Peterhead vs Queen's Park live scores & match info &#124; Soccerway|website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref>

=== Dundee United ===
19-year-old Robertson and his Queen's Park teammate [[Aidan Connolly]], signed for [[Scottish Premiership]] side [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]<ref name=":1">{{cite news |date=3 June 2013 |title=Dundee Utd sign Queen's Park's Robertson and Connolly |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22762888 |access-date=5 August 2013 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> on 3 June 2013.<ref name=":1" /> Robertson replaced departing [[Barry Douglas]], who had made the same move three years earlier.<ref>{{cite web |title=Barry Douglas Joins United |url=https://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/news/2895/BARRY-DOUGLAS-JOINS-UNITED.html |date=21 June 2010 |access-date=9 January 2019 |website=Dundee United Football Club}}</ref> Having had requests ignored for a transfer fee for Douglas, Queen's Park (then an amateur club) protested at the prospect of more players departing to United for free. The two clubs agreed a deal involving a percentage of future transfers, later benefiting Queen's with £300 000.<ref>{{cite web |date=27 July 2014 |title=£300k Robertson boost a cut above for Queen's Park |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/13172018.300k-robertson-boost-a-cut-above-for-queens-park/ |access-date=23 July 2025 |website=The Herald}}</ref>

[[Jackie McNamara]] was Robertson's manager at Dundee United. Robertson later remarked, "Jackie McNamara had been a great full-back [at Celtic] and he helped me."<ref name=guachafin/> Robertson later also said [[John Rankin (footballer, born 1983)|John Rankin]], "effectively talked me through games in my first three months."<ref name=notthero>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nottheoldfirm.com/news/liverpool-robertson-dundee-united-teammate-rankin/|title=Liverpool hero Robertson thanks former Dundee United teammate Rankin|first=Ben|last=Banks|date=18 December 2019|website=Not The Old Firm}}</ref> Rankin also conscientiously covered the spaces left when Robertson went on an attacking run.<ref name=":0"/>

Robertson debuted for United in an opening day of the [[2013–14 in Scottish football|league]] season 0–0 draw at [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref name=sb>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=65797&season_id=143|title=Andy Robertson &#124; Football Stats &#124; Liverpool &#124; Season 2013/2014 &#124; Soccer Base|website=www.soccerbase.com}}</ref> On 22 September 2013, Robertson scored his first Dundee United goal, drawing 2–2 at home with [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Crawford |first=Kenny |date=22 September 2013 |title=Dundee United 2–2 Motherwell |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24098544 |access-date=23 September 2013 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He ran from his own half before sending a low left-foot drive in to the goal from 22 yards.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/dundee-utd-2-2-motherwell-ainsworth-stuns-utd-1-3106278 |title=Dundee Utd 2–2 Motherwell: Ainsworth stuns Utd |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=22 September 2013 |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> Soon afterwards he agreed a new contract with United, until May 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dundee secure Robertson extension |url=http://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/index.asp?tm=2&nid=4617&cd=2013 |publisher=Dundee United F.C. |date=4 October 2013 |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> He was voted [[Scottish Professional Football League monthly awards|SPFL young player of the month]] for September 2013 and player of the month for November 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 September 2021 |title=Evening Telegraph The Courier Combined |url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/evening-telegraph-the-courier-combined/ |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=The Courier |language=en-GB}}</ref>

As well as Robertson, other recent and/or future full Scotland internationalists in that [[2013–14 Dundee United F.C. season|2013–14 Dundee United]] squad were [[Stuart Armstrong]], [[Gary Mackay-Steven]], [[Mark Wilson (Scottish footballer)|Mark Wilson]], [[Ryan Gauld]] and [[John Souttar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/teams/te511/dundee-united/squad/|title=Dundee United – Squad 2013/2014|date=26 April 2025|website=worldfootball.net}}</ref> On 12 April 2014, Robertson played in the [[2013–14 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]] 3–1 semi-final win versus [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]]. Armstrong and Mackay-Steven scored, as did [[Nadir Çiftçi]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Rangers 1–3 Dundee United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26898652 |website=BBC Sport |last=Wilson |first=Richard |date=12 April 2014 |access-date=24 April 2014}}</ref> In April 2014, Robertson won the [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year]] award,<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 April 2014 |title=Three Celtic players make PFA player of year shortlist |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27052382 |access-date=24 April 2014 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=27 April 2014 |title=Andrew Robertson: Dundee United defender wins PFA prize |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27183894 |access-date=17 May 2014 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> and was named in the [[PFA Scotland Team of the Year]] for the [[2013–14 Scottish Premiership]].<ref name="toy14">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27080030 |title=Celtic and Dundee United trios in SPFL Premiership team of year |date=18 April 2014 |access-date=24 April 2014 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Robertson and United finished the season fourth best team in the league in Scotland.<ref name=":2"/>

His last appearance for United was in the [[2014 Scottish Cup Final]]. With the score at 0–0, [[Ryan Dow]]'s flicked volley hit the post from Robertson's first time cross into the penalty area. [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] won 2–0.<ref name=scocupfin>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nseo86l4GLY|title=Scottish Cup Final 2014 // St. Johnstone 2–0 Dundee United|date=18 May 2014|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27354162 |title=St Johnstone 2–0 Dundee United |first=Richard |last=Wilson |website=BBC Sport |date=17 May 2014 |access-date=23 December 2018}}</ref>

=== Hull City ===
[[File: Andy Robertson (19596759769).jpg|thumb|upright|Robertson playing for [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] in 2015]]

Aged 20, on 29 July 2014 Robertson signed a three-year contract<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/dundee-united/284200-andrew-robertson-completes-transfer-from-dundee-united-to-hull/ |title=Andrew Robertson completes transfer from Dundee United to Hull |date=29 July 2014 |website=STV Sport |access-date=20 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730093640/http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/dundee-united/284200-andrew-robertson-completes-transfer-from-dundee-united-to-hull/ |archive-date=30 July 2014}}</ref> with English [[Premier League]] club [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28442322 |title=Andrew Robertson: Dundee United agree fee with Hull City |website=BBC Sport |date=24 July 2014 |access-date=24 July 2014 |first=Jim |last=Spence}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Transfer news: Hull City sign defenders Harry Maguire and Andrew Robertson |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/9399176/premier-league-hull-city-sign-defenders-harry-maguire-and-andrew-robertson |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> The transfer fee was £2.85&nbsp;million. Hull City's chief scout, [[Stan Ternent]], explained, "I'd been looking at [[Stuart Armstrong]] but [Robertson] was the no brainer … he'd a history with Celtic and he was always a determined lad given how he'd recovered from his setbacks. You could see straight away he had ability and he can only get better."<ref>{{cite web |last=Buckingham |first=Philip |date=2 June 2019 |title=How Hull City helped Andy Robertson to win the Champions League |url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/andy-robertson-liverpool-champions-league-1610379 |access-date=9 June 2019 |website=Hull Daily Mail}}</ref>

Robertson made a goal-line clearance debuting on the opening day of the [[2014–15 Premier League]] season. Hull won 1–0 at [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]].<ref>{{cite web |last=McDermott |first=Scott |date=24 August 2014 |title=Andrew Robertson admits his rise to stardom is difficult to comprehend |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/hull-defender-andrew-robertson-admits-4098535 |access-date=5 March 2021 |website=Daily Record}}</ref> That August he was Hull's Player of the Month.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robertson |first1=Neil |date=17 September 2014 |title=Andrew Robertson named Hull City's player of the month |url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/sport/football/dundee-united/136743/andrew-robertson-named-hull-citys-player-of-the-month/ |access-date=24 November 2014 |website=The Courier |language=en-GB}}</ref> He made 24 Hull appearances that season, all in the league.<ref name="Soccerway"/> Hull finished 18th in the 20 team division that season, for relegation to the [[EFL Championship|Championship]]. [[Hatem Ben Arfa]] predicted of his relegated Hull teammates, "There's one who can be super, super, super good … and that's Robertson."<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Henderson |first=Lewis |date=19 February 2019 |title=How Andy Robertson rose from rejection and amateur football to become one of Europe's best left-backs |url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2019/02/19/how-andy-robertson-rose-from-rejection-and-amateur-football-to-become-one-of-europes-best-left-backs/ |access-date=9 June 2019 |website=These Football Times |language=en-GB}}</ref>

Robertson scored the opener for his first Hull goal on 3 November 2015 at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. That 2–0 win put Hull top of the Championship table.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34644748 |title=Brentford 0–2 Hull |date=3 November 2015 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=4 November 2015}}</ref> He started the [[2016 Football League Championship play-off final|2016 Championship play-off final]] against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]. Hull won 1–0 for promotion to the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Williams |title=Hull City 1–0 Sheffield Wednesday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36348885 |website=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2016 |access-date=22 December 2017}}</ref> Robertson played in 52 Hull games in all competitions that season.<ref name="Soccerway"/>

Hull spent one season back in the top flight before being relegated at the end of the [[2016–17 Premier League|2016–17 season]]. Like two years before, they finished 18th in the 20 team division.<ref name=":2" /> He played in 39 Hull league and cup games that season.<ref name="Soccerway"/>

Robertson and fellow Hull defender [[Harry Maguire]] were recommended by [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] scout [[Steve Walsh (scout)|Steve Walsh]] to transfer in a combined £20&nbsp;million deal, but Everton rejected the proposal.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Young |first=Alex |date=18 November 2019 |title=Everton rejected 'cut-price Robertson, Maguire and Haaland deals' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/everton-rejected-cutprice-andy-robertson-harry-maguire-erling-haaland-deals-a4289616.html |access-date=5 March 2021 |website=The Standard}}</ref>

=== Liverpool ===
==== 2017–2019 ====
[[File:Liver-RM (10).jpg|thumb|upright|Robertson playing for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[2018 UEFA Champions League final]]]]

Aged 23, on 21 July 2017 Robertson signed a long-term contract with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] under the management of [[Jürgen Klopp]]. The fee was an initial £8&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/269167-liverpool-fc-complete-andy-robertson-signing |title=Liverpool FC complete Andy Robertson signing |date=21 July 2017 |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=21 July 2017 |title=Andrew Robertson: Liverpool sign defender from Hull City for £10m |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40666486 |access-date=21 July 2017 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Liverpool seal deal for left-back Robertson |url=https://www.anews.com.tr/sport/2017/07/21/liverpool-seal-deal-for-left-back-robertson |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=anews}}</ref> [[Kevin Stewart (footballer)|Kevin Stewart]] went to Hull City at the same time for almost the same amount, in what has been described as a swap deal in all but name.<ref name=thisisrob>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2018/06/andy-robertson-2017-18-season-review-liverpools-left-back-problem-finally-solved/|title=How Liverpool finally solved their left-back problem|first=James|last=Nalton|date=4 June 2018}}</ref>

On 19 August, Robertson made his debut for Liverpool in a 1–0 league win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gorst |first=Paul |date=19 August 2017 |title=Robertson thanks Liverpool fans after impressing on Reds debut |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/andy-robertson-thanks-liverpool-fans-13501385 |access-date=31 August 2017 |website=Liverpool Echo |language=en}}</ref> He was given the Man of the Match award.<ref name=":0" />

Robertson started the 2017–18 season as [[Alberto Moreno]]'s understudy.<ref name=echopat/> Moreno had a bright start to the season,<ref name=thisisrob/> meaning Robertson played only two further games before December.<ref name="Soccerway"/> Moreno then injured his ankle,<ref name=echopat>{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Neil |date=16 January 2018 |title=Klopp's patience key for Robertson and Oxlade-Chamberlain |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/klopps-patience-key-andy-robertson-14164148 |access-date=8 April 2025|website=Liverpool Echo}}</ref> opening the first team opportunity for Robertson to grab on 2 December. Liverpool that day won 5–1 at home in the league against [[Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton and Hove Albion]].<ref name="Soccerway"/>

Robertson's 70-yard pressing run late in his man of the match performance,<ref name=thisisrob/> in a 4–3 win against league leaders [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], on 14 January 2018 went viral with Robertson elevated to cult hero among Liverpool fans.<ref name=":2"/><ref name=culrun>{{Cite web|url=https://www.givemesport.com/1236153-the-moment-andrew-robertson-made-himself-a-liverpool-cult-hero-vs-man-city/|title=The moment Andrew Robertson made himself a Liverpool cult hero vs Man City|first=Danny|last=Ryan|date=14 January 2018|website=GiveMeSport}}</ref> Robertson scored his first Liverpool goal in the last game of the [[2017–18 Premier League|2017–18 season]], an 4–0 home win against [[Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton and Hove Albion]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44020158 |title=Salah breaks record as Liverpool secure top four spot |last=Jennings |first=Patrick |date=13 May 2018 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=13 May 2018}}</ref>

He played the full 90 minutes of the [[2018 UEFA Champions League final]], 3–1 defeat to Real Madrid in [[Kyiv]].<ref name="uefa18">{{Cite web |last=UEFA.com |title=History: Real Madrid 3-1 Liverpool: UEFA Champions League 2017/18 Final |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2021711--real-madrid-vs-liverpool/ |access-date=25 May 2026 |website=UEFA.com |language=en}}</ref> The Independent wrote, "Robertson was one of Liverpool's more impressive players on the night, the highlight of his display being an expertly-timed last-ditch tackle to prevent [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] from scoring."<ref name=indtack>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/mohamed-salah-injury-update-liverpool-news-andy-robertson-real-madrid-a8371926.html|title=Mohamed Salah's injury was the turning point in Liverpool's defeat, says Andy Robertson |website=[[Independent.co.uk]] |date=27 May 2018 }}</ref> Robertson ended the season with 30 appearances in all competitions, including 22 in the Premier League and 6 in the UEFA Champions League.<ref name="Soccerway"/>

Robertson signed a new contract with the club in January 2019, due to run until 2024.<ref name=":3">{{cite news |date=17 January 2019 |title=Andy Robertson: Liverpool & Scotland defender signs new contract until 2024 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46911501 |access-date=18 January 2019 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> In the 2018–19 Premier League season, Robertson registered 11 [[Assist (association football)|assists]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Robertson breaks FPL records with assists double |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1199511 |access-date=2 September 2021 |website=www.premierleague.com |date=26 April 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/04/26/assist-king-andy-robertson-delighted-equals-incredible-premier-league-record-huddersfield-win-9326447/ |title=Assist king Andy Robertson delighted as he equals incredible Premier League record |date=26 April 2019 |website=Metro |access-date=2 September 2021}}</ref> Liverpool finished the [[2018–19 Premier League|league season]] as runners-up to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], to whom they suffered their only league defeat. Liverpool's 97 points was the then third-highest total in the history of the English top division. It was also the most points scored by a team without winning the title. Liverpool were unbeaten at home in the league for a consecutive season and matched the club record of 30 league wins in a season.<ref name="Wolves">{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Daniel |title=Sadio Mané double sinks Wolves but Liverpool's title wait goes on |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/may/12/liverpool-wolves-premier-league-match-report |access-date=1 June 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |agency=The Guardian |date=12 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Neill |first1=Caoimhe |title=Anfield's amazing response to Premier League disappointment as Man City beat Liverpool to title |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/anfields-amazing-response-premier-league-16264309 |access-date=1 June 2019 |work=liverpoolecho.co.uk |publisher=Liverpool Echo |date=12 May 2019}}</ref> On 25 April, Robertson was named in the 2018–19 [[PFA Team of the Year]] alongside Liverpool teammates [[Trent Alexander-Arnold]], [[Sadio Mané]] and [[Virgil van Dijk]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2019/4/25/premier-league-team-of-the-year |title=PFA Premier League Team of the Year |publisher=Professional Footballers' Association |date=25 April 2019 |access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> the following season, he was named in the team [[PFA Team of the Year (2020s)#2019-20|a second time]].

On 7 May 2019, Robertson started in the 4–0 UEFA Champions League semi-final second-leg, home win against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]. Described as "one of the most memorable comebacks of all time", that overturned the 1st leg 3–0 defeat. Robertson subbed off injured, 1–0 at half-time after being kicked by [[Luis Suárez]].<ref name=guabarca>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/may/07/liverpool-v-barcelona-champions-league-semi-final-second-leg-live|title=Liverpool 4–0 Barcelona (4–3 agg): Champions League semi-final – as it happened|first=Barry|last=Glendenning|work=the Guardian |date=7 May 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>

On 1 June 2019, Robertson played the full 90 minutes of the [[2019 UEFA Champions League final|UEFA Champions League final]] an 2–0 win against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in Madrid, securing Liverpool's sixth European Cup title.<ref name=":4">{{cite news |date=2 June 2019 |title=Liverpool can 'kick-on' from 'incredible' Champions League win – Andy Robertson |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48489952 |access-date=2 June 2019 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He became the first Scotsman to win the final since [[Darren Fletcher]] (an unused substitute in [[2008 UEFA Champions League final|2008]]),<ref>{{cite web |date=1 June 2019 |title=Scotland captain Andy Robertson, and his Liverpool teammates, join the greats |url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/17678775.scotland-captain-andy-robertson-and-his-liverpool-teammates-join-the-greats/ |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=Glasgow Times}}</ref> and the first to play in the final winning team since [[Paul Lambert]] in [[1997 UEFA Champions League final|1997]].<ref name=":4" />

==== 2019–2021 ====
[[File:LFC Parade 2019 01 Andy Robertson.jpg|thumb|Robertson celebrating Liverpool's [[2019 UEFA Champions League final|2019 Champions League victory]]]]
Robertson started the [[2019 UEFA Super Cup]] penalty shootout win against Chelsea in [[Istanbul]]. He was substituted in the 91st minute with the score at 1–1; the score ended 2–2 after extra-time.<ref name=ueflivche>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/match/2025638--liverpool-vs-chelsea/|title=Liverpool vs Chelsea &#124; UEFA Super Cup 2019 Final|website=UEFA.com}}</ref>

In December, Robertson played in the [[2019 FIFA Club World Cup]] 2–1 semi-final win over [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]].<ref name=espnmont>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/557726/liverpool-monterrey|title=Liverpool 2–1 Monterrey (Dec 18, 2019) Final Score|website=ESPN}}</ref> He then played the entirety of the final, a 1–0 extra-time win over [[CR Flamengo|Flamengo]].<ref name=guafla>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/dec/21/liverpool-v-flamengo-club-world-cup-final-2019-live|title=Liverpool 1–0 Flamengo: Club World Cup final 2019 – as it happened!|first=Simon|last=Burnton|work=the Guardian |date=21 December 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>

In Liverpool's first [[2019–20 UEFA Champions League]] home game on 2 October, Robertson scored his first European goal against [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]]; Liverpool won 4-3.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bicknell |first=Gareth |date=3 October 2019 |title=Andy Robertson hails Liverpool teammate after goal against Red Bull Salzburg |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/andy-robertson-hails-liverpool-teammate-20392395 |access-date=3 October 2019 |website=Daily Mirror}}</ref> On 2 November 2019, Robertson scored his second Liverpool Premier League goal, equalising in the 87th minute against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]; Liverpool went on to win that game 1-2 in stoppage time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leaders Liverpool fight back to down Villa |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50190998 |date=2 November 2019 |access-date=2 November 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In the [[2019–20 Liverpool F.C. season|2019–20]] domestic campaign, Robertson contributed 2 goals and 12 assists for Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/10458/Andrew-Robertson/stats |title=2019/2020 Premier League Player Stats |publisher=Premier League |access-date=3 August 2020}}</ref>

In the 2020–21 season, the majority of games were played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in England|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/fans/behind-closed-doors/home|title=Reds Behind Closed Doors 20/21|work=Liverpool FC|access-date=26 May 2021}}</ref> On 22 November 2020, Liverpool broke the club record for longest unbeaten run at home in the league (which had previously stood at 63) with a 3–0 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/nov/22/liverpool-leicester-premier-league-match-report|title=Jota strikes again as Liverpool ease to record-breaking win over Leicester|date=22 November 2020|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 February 2021}}</ref> That run ended on 21 January 2021 following a 1–0 defeat to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]; it had stood at 68, the second-longest unbeaten home run in English top-flight history, behind [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s run of 86 games between March 2004 and October 2008, and the longest under a single manager.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.skysports.com/football/live-blog/11661/12191694/liverpool-vs-burnley-live|title= Liverpool 0–1 Burnley highlights|date=21 January 2021|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=9 March 2021}}</ref> Robertson remained first choice left-back, starting 48 of the 50 games he played.<ref name="Soccerway"/>

==== 2021–2023 ====
On 24 August 2021, Robertson signed a new long-term contract with Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web |title=Andy Robertson signs new long-term contract with Liverpool FC |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/441568-andy-robertson-signs-new-long-term-contract-with-liverpool-fc |publisher=Liverpool FC |access-date=24 August 2021 |date=24 August 2021}}</ref> He and Liverpool missed out on winning a historic quadruple that season. They defeated [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in penalty shootouts in both the [[2021–22 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] (11–10) and [[2021–22 FA Cup|FA Cup]] (6–5) finals. Both finals were 0–0 after extra time. Robertson scored his team's eighth penalty in the 11–10 win.<ref name=espncara>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/628732/liverpool-chelsea|title=Liverpool 0–0 Chelsea (Feb 27, 2022) Final Score|website=ESPN}}</ref> However, they finished second in the [[2021–22 Premier League|Premier League]] and were runners up in the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], losing [[2022 UEFA Champions League final|the final]] 1–0 in Paris to Real Madrid.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Liverpool's quadruple, treble chase is over: Reds settle for double in 2021–22 |website=Sporting News |url= https://www.sportingnews.com/uk/football/news/liverpool-quadruple-chase-2021-22-reds-man-united-treble/pmwqorelovih6pge6xnpv3av#:~:text=The%20Reds%20were%20battling%20on,making%20history%20with%20a%20quadruple. |access-date=2 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61609200 |title=Liverpool 0–1 Real Madrid |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2022 |access-date=28 February 2023 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606200753/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61609200 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was selected as part of the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League#Team of the season|UEFA Champions League Team of the Season]].<ref>{{cite news |title=2021/22 UEFA Champions League Team of the Season |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0275-154650014aef-02a394f30379-1000--official-team-of-the-season/ |publisher=UEFA |date=31 May 2022 |access-date=31 May 2022 |archive-date=6 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220606205239/https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0275-154650014aef-02a394f30379-1000--official-team-of-the-season/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

At the start of the 2022–23 season, Robertson and Liverpool won the [[2022 FA Community Shield|FA Community Shield]]. That piece of silverware meant that both manager Jürgen Klopp and Robertson had won all seven available first-tier trophies with Liverpool.<ref name=tro90min>{{Cite web|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/every-trophy-jurgen-klopp-has-won-at-liverpool|title=Every trophy Jurgen Klopp has won at Liverpool|date=28 February 2023|website=90min.com}}</ref> On 26 December 2022 in a 1–3 win at [[Aston Villa]], Robertson became the defender with most [[Assist (association football)|assists]] in Premier League history with 54; surpassing previous record [[Leighton Baines]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64098407 |title=Liverpool: Andy Robertson becomes defender with most Premier League assists |website=BBC Sport |date=26 December 2022 |accessdate=27 December 2022}}</ref>

==== 2023–present ====
[[File:Andrew Robertson 04012026 (2).jpg|thumb|upright|Robertson warming up for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2026]]

On 16 September 2023, with captain [[Virgil van Dijk]] suspended and vice-captain [[Trent Alexander-Arnold]] injured, Robertson was made captain for a 3–1 comeback win against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]. He marked his 200th Premier League appearance for Liverpool by scoring Liverpool's second goal in that game; his 9th Liverpool goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-vs-liverpool/report/482640 |title=Liverpool go top with comeback against Wolves |website= Sky Sports|date=16 September 2023|accessdate=16 September 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fisher |first=Ben |date=16 September 2023 |title=Andy Robertson's late strike powers Liverpool's fightback win at Wolves |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/sep/16/wolves-liverpool-premier-league-match-report |access-date=19 September 2023 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0029-7712}}</ref>

On 25 February 2024, Robertson and Liverpool defeated Chelsea 1–0 after extra-time, winning the [[2024 EFL Cup final]].<ref name=livche24>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/697787/liverpool-chelsea|title=Liverpool 1–0 Chelsea (Feb 25, 2024) Final Score|website=ESPN}}</ref> Robertson managed only 30 appearances for Liverpool that season,<ref name="Soccerway"/> as a shoulder injured while playing for Scotland against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in October 2023 sidelined him until January 2024.<ref name=guashou>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/oct/20/liverpool-andy-robertson-faces-three-months-out-with-shoulder-injury|title=Liverpool's Andy Robertson faces three months out with shoulder injury|first=Andy|last=Hunter|work=The Guardian |date=20 October 2023}}</ref>

On 1 September 2024, after a 3–0 win over [[Liverpool F.C.-Manchester United F.C. rivalry|rivals]] [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], Robertson was among those to comment on the defensive solidarity under new manager [[Arne Slot]], as opposed to high-risk [[Association football tactics and skills#"Forward" versus "collapsing" defences|gegenpressing]] under Jürgen Klopp. Robertson added, "We look a bit more secure defensively."<ref name=mirstyle>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/liverpool-slot-klopp-alisson-robertson-33580285|title=Alisson and Robertson hit nail on head when comparing Arne Slot to Jurgen Klopp|first=Daniel|last=Orme|date=2 September 2024|website=Daily Mirror}}</ref> Robertson added later in the season, "It was obviously a different style [back then], It was high energy and high press. This team is a bit more controlled. Two very different teams."<ref name=ffstyle>{{Cite web|url=https://thefootballfaithful.com/robertson-difference-between-liverpool-title-wins/|title=Robertson explains difference between Liverpool title wins|first=Ste|last=McGovern|date=27 April 2025}}</ref> An article from [[Fara Williams]] in May 2025 analysing the impact of Slot's style of play on Robertson included, "You think back to the Klopp teams in terms of how high up the pitch both Trent and Robertson used to play and how aggressive they were in terms of their start position. That has changed under Arne Slot." Williams added, "He (Slot) is more patient in how they build. They don't leave themselves too exposed to transitions. They are not as expansive through their full-backs. We talk about how well their midfield has played this year, a lot of play has gone through the midfield, whereas under Klopp, they went more down the outside. So there has been a lot of differences, a lot of changes in the system, and that affects personnel. You can even look at the amount of time Robertson and [[Trent Alexander-Arnold|Alexander-Arnold]] have been on the pitch together and I don't think that has happened as much as before."<ref name=bbcfara>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cg5v23nnqzqo|title=Liverpool news: Has Arne Slot's style impacted Andy Robertson?|date=15 May 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Slot explained in November 2024 that Robertson being rotated in selection was due to him missing pre-season training.<ref name=rota>{{Cite web|url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/arne-slot-discusses-andy-robertsons-form-amid-unprecedented-rotation-40249873|title=Arne Slot discusses Andy Robertson's form amid unprecedented rotation|date=4 September 2025|website=OneFootball}}</ref> Slot then praised Robertson, despite receiving a red card in the 17th minute in a 2–2 home draw with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 14 December.<ref name=fulred>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-independent.com/sport/football/arne-slot-fulham-andy-robertson-liverpool-marco-silva-b2664483.html|title=Arne Slot praises Andy Robertson despite red card as Liverpool held by Fulham|date=14 December 2024|website=The Independent}}</ref> Robertson made 45 appearances that season<ref name="Soccerway"/> as he won his second [[2024-25 Premier League|Premier League title]].<ref name=medal25>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-au/news/which-liverpool-players-get-premier-league-winners-medal/blt91823e9e68510033|title=Which Liverpool players get a 2024–25 Premier League winners medal and who misses out? &#124; Goal.com Australia|date=28 April 2025|website=www.goal.com}}</ref>

On 29 August 2025, following the departure of Trent Alexander-Arnold to Real Madrid, 31-year-old Robertson became Liverpool's new vice-captain, acting as deputy to Virgil van Dijk.<ref name=vc>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/andy-robertson-appointed-liverpools-vice-captain|title=Andy Robertson appointed Liverpool's vice-captain – Liverpool FC|last1=Carroll|first1=James|last2=Shaw|first2=Chris|date=29 August 2025|website=www.liverpoolfc.com}}</ref> Despite that, he initially lost his starting spot in the first five games of the new season to new signing [[Miloš Kerkez]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c0q7e5kpl92o|title=What does Robertson's Liverpool situation mean for Scotland?|last=Canavan|first=Amy|date=4 September 2025|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=5 September 2025}}</ref> Robertson was restored as first choice left-back and Kerkez was benched on 17 September 2025, for the 3–2 [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League league phase|UEFA Champions League]] home win against [[Atlético Madrid]]. Robertson delivered a positively-received performance, also scoring the opener from a [[Mohamed Salah]] free-kick.<ref name=athle>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liverpool.com/liverpool-fc-news/features/alexander-isak-virgil-van-dijk-32498208|title=Alexander Isak message loud and clear as Virgil van Dijk saves Liverpool again|first=Matt|last=Addison|date=17 September 2025|website=Liverpool.com}}</ref> After Kerkez was restored as the first-choice left-back, Robertson was linked with a transfer to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] during the January 2026 transfer window; however, the offer was reportedly rejected due to Liverpool's inability to recall [[Kostas Tsimikas]] from his own [[Loan (sports)|loan spell]] at [[AS Roma|Roma]].<ref name="departure">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cp8d4jvj108o |first=Lorraine |last=McKenna |title=Andy Robertson: Liverpool defender to leave club at the end of the season |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=9 April 2026 |accessdate=10 April 2026}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Rampling |first=Ali |last2=Evans |first2=Gregg |date=9 April 2026 |title=Liverpool announce Andy Robertson to leave club at end of season |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6994291/2026/04/09/andy-robertson-liverpool-exit/ |access-date=10 April 2026 |work=[[The Athletic]] |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On 9 April 2026, Robertson announced that he would leave Liverpool at the end of the season, following the expiry of his contract.<ref name="departure" /><ref>{{Cite web |date=9 April 2026 |title=Andy Robertson to leave Liverpool at the end of this season |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/andy-robertson-leave-liverpool-end-season |access-date=9 April 2026 |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |language=en}}</ref> He made his final appearance for Liverpool in an 1–1 draw with [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] at Anfield on 24 May 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/13546576/liverpool-1-1-brentford-mohamed-salah-and-andy-roberson-say-goodbye-to-anfield-as-bees-miss-out-on-europe|title= Liverpool 1-1 Brentford: Mohamed Salah and Andy Robertson say goodbye to Anfield as Bees miss out on Europe|date=24 May 2026|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=25 May 2026}}</ref>

=== Tottenham Hotspur ===
On 5 June 2026, fellow Premier League club Tottenham Hotspur announced the signing of Robertson as a free agent.<ref name="Tottenham">{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/1071931/robertson-signing-secured |title=Robertson signing secured |date=5 June 2026 |publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |access-date=5 June 2026}}</ref>

== International career ==
[[File:Andrew Robertson v Russia 2019 (cropped2).jpg|thumb|upright|Robertson with [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in 2019]]

===Under-21s===
Robertson debuted internationally for [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21s]] on 10 October 2013, subbing on in a 2–1 win in [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] against [[Slovakia national under-21 football team|Slovakia]].<ref name=sfa>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=63749|title=Andy Robertson &#124; Scotland &#124; Scottish FA|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk}}</ref> He was selected for the under-21 team in November 2015, when the full national team did not have a fixture.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34701509 |title=Scotland U21s include Andy Robertson for Ukraine match |website=BBC Sport |date=2 November 2015 |access-date=4 November 2015}}</ref>

===Senior squad===
Robertson was first named in the full [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad for a friendly against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] on 5 March 2014. He played for Dundee United at the time. He subbed on in the second half, as Scotland won 1–0 in Warsaw.<ref name="poland">{{cite news |date=5 March 2014 |title=Scott Brown late show gives Scotland impressive win over Poland in Warsaw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/mar/05/poland-scotland-friendly-international-match-report |access-date=24 July 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> Scotland manager [[Gordon Strachan]] said afterwards "Andy came on there and the first time he picked it up he drove about 30 yards. I thought 'that's fantastic'. Absolutely no grey area, I'm going to do what I do. I loved seeing that first touch."<ref name=poland />

Robertson made his first start for the national team in a 2–2 draw at [[Craven Cottage]] with [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] on 28 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27383284 |quote=Scotland's new-look back four, which included Dundee United's Andrew Robertson making his first international start, found themselves under pressure when they conceded possession to Uchebo but Allan McGregor saved the shot. |title=Nigeria 2–2 Scotland |first=Andy |last=Campbell |website=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2014 |access-date=24 July 2014}}</ref> Robertson scored his first international goal in November 2014, losing a friendly 3–1 to [[England national football team|England]] at [[Celtic Park]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29999555 |title=Scotland 1–3 England |date=18 November 2014 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=20 November 2014}}</ref>

On 3 September 2018, Robertson was appointed [[List of Scotland national football team captains|Scotland captain]] by manager [[Alex McLeish]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/314927-andy-robertson-scotland-captain |title=Andy Robertson appointed new Scotland captain |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Shaw |first=Chris |date=3 September 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227170432/https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/314927-andy-robertson-scotland-captain |archive-date=27 December 2019}}</ref> After a 2–1 defeat against [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in October 2018, Robertson said that both he and fellow left-back [[Kieran Tierney]] were being played out of position in the [[Formation (association football)#3–5–2|3–5–2 system]] adopted by McLeish to accommodate both players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45832123 |title=Andy Robertson: Kieran Tierney and I are 'both out of position' |website=BBC Sport |date=12 October 2018 |access-date=13 October 2018}}</ref>

====Steve Clarke era: 2019–present====
After the sacking of Alex McLeish, [[Steve Clarke]] was appointed manager of Scotland in May 2019; he elected to keep Robertson as captain.<ref name=Scotland>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48303984 |title=Steve Clarke is named new Scotland manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 May 2019 |access-date=20 May 2019}}</ref> In Clarke's first game as Scotland manager, a [[UEFA Euro 2020]] [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group I|qualifier]] against [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] on 8 June 2019, Robertson scored the opener with a long-range strike. Scotland went on to win 2–1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/scotland-vs-cyprus-result-euro-2020-qualifying-oliver-burke-goal-john-mcginn-a8950926.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220507/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/scotland-vs-cyprus-result-euro-2020-qualifying-oliver-burke-goal-john-mcginn-a8950926.html |archive-date=7 May 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Scotland vs Cyprus result: Euro 2020 qualifying hopes still alive after last-gasp win says John McGinn |last=Esplin |first=Ronnie |date=9 June 2019 |newspaper=The Independent |access-date=9 June 2019}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In October's  qualifiers against [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] and [[Russia national football team|Russia]], Robertson was reunited with former [[QPFC|Queen's Park]] teammate [[Lawrence Shankland]], the two having last played together for then-amateur [[QPFC|Queen's Park]] in the [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Scottish Third Division]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/17939061.queens-park-share-nostalgic-snap-robertson-shankland-teammates-scotland-call-up|title=Queen's Park share nostalgic snap of Robertson and Shankland as teammates after Scotland call-up|last=Hendry|first=Mark|date=1 October 2019|work=Glasgow Times|access-date=10 September 2021}}</ref> In November 2020, with Robertson again as captain, Scotland qualified for [[UEFA Euro 2020]] following a play-off 5–4 win on penalties against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] in [[Belgrade]]. It was Scotland's first major tournament qualification since 1998, ending a 22-year non-qualifying streak.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watt |first1=Martin |date=23 November 2020 |title=Serbia 1–1 Scotland: Visitors win 5–4 on penalties to end 23-year finals wait |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54819938 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |access-date=23 November 2020}}</ref>

On 14 June 2021, Robertson captained Scotland in their first Euro 2020 game, losing 2–0 to the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51197776 |title=Scotland 0–2 Czech Republic |first=Scott |last=Mullen |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2021 |accessdate=14 June 2021}}</ref> After a 0–0 draw with England at [[Wembley Stadium]], Scotland were knocked out at the group stage after losing 3–1 to [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref name=guacro>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2021/jun/22/croatia-v-scotland-euro-2020-live-score-updates|title=Croatia 3–1 Scotland: Euro 2020 – as it happened|first=Paul|last=Doyle|work=the Guardian |date=22 June 2021|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> On 4 September 2021, Robertson won his 50th cap and thereby joined the [[Scottish FA International Roll of Honour]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Pattullo |first=Alan |date=6 September 2021 |title=Andy Robertson reveals 'calm down' chat with Nathan Patterson as Rangers kid hailed for Scotland display |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/international/robertson-reveals-calm-down-chat-with-patterson-after-scotland-opener-3371745 |access-date=10 September 2021 |website=The Scotsman}}</ref> In his next game, he led the team to a 0–1 away win against [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58386792|title=Austria 0–1 Scotland|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Martin|last=Watt|date=7 September 2021|access-date=10 September 2021}}</ref> Akin to Robertson reuniting with Shankland two years prior, [[Paul McGinn]] made his debut against Austria; reuniting him and Robertson for the first time in almost nine years since appearing together with Queen's Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/hibs/andrew-robertson-and-paul-mcginns-last-game-together-before-steering-scotland-to-crucial-1-0-win-over-austria-in-qatar-2022-world-cup-qualifier-3375159|title=Andrew Robertson and Paul McGinn's last game together before steering Scotland to crucial 1–0 win over Austria in Qatar 2022 World Cup qualifier|last=Oliver|first=David|date=8 September 2021|work=The Scotsman|access-date=10 September 2021}}</ref>

[[File:First Minister meets with Scottish National Football Team (3).jpg|thumb|right|Robertson (right) with [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], in 2026]]

Late goals from [[Lyndon Dykes]] and [[Kenny McLean]] earned Scotland a comeback 1-2 win against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] in Oslo in June 2023. Robertson was named man of the match, and was described by [[BBC Sport]]'s Thomas Duncan as having "led by example... composed at the back and brilliant at driving the team forward up the left, he barely put a foot wrong."<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65864111 |title= Norway 1-2 Scotland|work=BBC Sport|access-date=18 June 2023}}</ref> This result put Scotland top of their [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] group on a maximum nine points from three games played;<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65941355 |title= Scotland: Andy Robertson says Scots 'have to qualify' after dream start|work=BBC Sport|access-date=18 June 2023}}</ref> having beaten [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] and [[Spain men's national football team|Spain]] in the two prior games. Scotland finished second in [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying Group A|Group A]] behind the latter, automatically qualifying them for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].

On 7 June 2024, Robertson was named in Scotland's squad for UEFA Euro 2024 in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=3 May 2024 |title=Scotland: Uefa confirms 26-man squads for Euro 2024 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/cd1dzg9982eo |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On the same day in a 2–2 friendly draw with [[Finland national football team|Finland]], he was Scotland captain for the 49th time; this surpassed [[George Young (Scottish footballer)|George Young]]'s record for the most games as captain of the Scotland men's national team.<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 June 2024 |title=Scotland: Roberston breaks record as most capped male captain |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/czkkn3rx327o |access-date=8 June 2024 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/clwwr7qeyx8t|title=Scotland lose two-goal lead to draw Euro 2024 send-off with Finland|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 14 June 2024, he started the opening match of Euro 2024. Scotland lost 5–1 to hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]], with [[Ryan Porteous]] sent off before half-time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> Robertson started in the 1–1 draw with [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and the 1–0 defeat to [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]]. With Scotland needing to win, Robertson in defence was replaced after 88 minutes by [[Lewis Morgan (footballer)|Lewis Morgan]] in attack. Hungary then counter-attacked in the 10th minute of stoppage time up Robertson's side of the pitch to score. Scotland were thus eliminated, bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three games.<ref name=hunscogua>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2024/jun/23/scotland-hungary-euro-2024-live|title=Scotland 0–1 Hungary: Euro 2024 – as it happened|first=Scott|last=Murray|work=the Guardian |date=23 June 2024|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1–1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref> On 18 November 2024, Robertson scored a stoppage-time winner in a [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League A|UEFA Nations League]], 2–1 win in Poland, that prevented Scotland's automatic relegation to League B, after finishing third in their group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cyv75jlmzq9t|title=Poland 1–2 Scotland|date=18 November 2024|access-date=18 November 2024|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Scotland though were subsequently relegated in the [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League promotion/relegation play-offs|relegation play-off]], losing 3–1 on aggregate to Greece.<ref name=guagree>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/mar/23/scotland-greece-nations-league-playoff-match-report|title=Scotland relegated in Nations League as Karetsas leads Greece demolition job|first=Ewan|last=Murray|work=The Guardian |date=23 March 2025}}</ref>

During [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group C|Scotland's 2026 World Cup qualifying campaign]], Robertson (in his seventh year as Scotland captain) provided two assists; in a 2-1 win vs [[Belarus national football team|Belarus]] and a 3-2 loss vs [[Greece men's national football team|Greece]]. On 18 November 2025, Scotland faced [[Denmark men's national football team|Denmark]] at Hampden Park, with Scotland needing only to win to automatically qualify for [[2026 FIFA World Cup|the tournament]]. On his 90th cap, Robertson led his country to a first [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] since [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]] in a famous 4–2 victory.<ref name="Canavan"/> He won his 92nd cap in a 1–0 defeat against [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]] on 31 March 2026,<ref name=sfa/><ref>{{Cite tweet |author=Match of the Day |author-link= |user=BBCMOTD |number=2039036649968161197 |date=31 March 2026 |title=A landmark night for Andy Robertson - he wins his 92nd cap and goes into second place for most appearances for Scotland! |script-title= |trans-title= |language=English |retweet=44 |location= |access-date=1 April 2026 |link=https://x.com/BBCMOTD/status/2039036649968161197 |url-status=|archive-url= |archive-date= |quote= |ref=}}</ref> making him the second-highest capped player in the country's history; he is currently second only to [[Kenny Dalglish]] with 102 caps.<ref name=sfaroll/>

== Style of play ==
During his prime between 2018 and 2022, Robertson was frequently described by pundits and media sources as one of the best left-backs in world football.<ref name="Marshall-Bailey">{{cite web |last=Marshall-Bailey |first=Tom |date=19 January 2019 |title=Andy Robertson labelled the best left-back in the Premier League |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/andy-robertson-labelled-best-left-15703038 |access-date=20 March 2019 |website=Liverpool Echo}}</ref><ref name="Treadwell">{{cite web |last=Treadwell |first=Matthew |date=13 January 2021 |title=Liverpool's Andy Robertson best left-back in world, says Jose Enrique |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12186169/liverpools-andy-robertson-best-left-back-in-world-says-jose-enrique#:~:text=Andy%20Robertson%20is%20Liverpool's%20player,first%20league%20title%20since%201990. |access-date=2 September 2021 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref name="Hubbuck">{{cite web |last=Hubbuck |first=Colin |date=7 July 2021 |title=The 10 Best Left Backs In The World Right Now, Named And Ranked |url=https://www.sportbible.com/football/53021-best-left-backs-world-right-now-20210707 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210708225327/https://www.sportbible.com/football/53021-best-left-backs-world-right-now-20210707 |archive-date=8 July 2021 |access-date=2 September 2021 |website=Sport Bible}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://sportmob.com/en/article/875490-Best-Left-Backs-in-the-World-in-2020 |title=Best Left-Backs in the World in 2020 |date=19 July 2021 |website=SportMob |access-date=2 September 2021 |archive-date=27 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230927224941/https://sportmob.com/en/article/875490-Best-Left-Backs-in-the-World-in-2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="Neville">{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/scotland/scotland-and-liverpool-ace-andy-robertson-best-left-back-in-the-world-says-neville-1-4886956 |title=Scotland and Liverpool ace Andy Robertson 'best left-back in the world' says Neville |last=Sked |first=Joel |date=11 March 2019 |website=The Scotsman |access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref> An online article specifically analysing Robertson's style (at the time under Klopp at Liverpool), highlighted defensively Robertson's, "discipline required to maintain the defensive integrity of the team", "ability to time his presses and regain possession," and "positional intelligence and awareness." The article added, "Robertson's defensive strategy involves proactive decision-making, calculated risks, and strategic positional play. This allows him to make crucial interceptions and regain possession for his team, [to] often launch counter-attacks." The same article described Robertson's attacking threat from his, "blistering pace", "exemplary assists", "work ethic", "dynamic overlapping runs" and "ability to exploit spaces and provide precise crosses helps his team create and convert chances".<ref name=titans>{{Cite web|url=https://thetitansfa.com/unleashing-andy-robertsons-defensive-and-attacking-skills/|title=Unleashing Andy Robertson's Defensive and Attacking Skills|date=13 February 2024}}</ref>

Former Manchester United manager [[José Mourinho]] commented in December 2018, after losing 3–1 to Liverpool, "I am still tired, just look[ing] at Robertson. He makes, I think, 100-metre sprints every minute. Absolutely incredible, and these are qualities."<ref name=mou>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mOGGyJbYVdc|title=Jose Mourinho admits he is 'still tired' from '200mph' Liverpool and 'incredible' Robertson display|author=Skillz Unleashed|date=16 December 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Jose Mourinho: I am still tired just looking at Andy Robertson |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/english-soccer/jose-mourinho-i-am-still-tired-just-looking-at-andy-robertson-1.3733357 |access-date=1 May 2024 |newspaper=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>

Robertson wrote in a 2019 self-penned article, "No magic wands have been waved in my direction, I didn't win some kind of lottery to land a spot on one of the biggest clubs in the world. The reason why I'm a Liverpool player is the same reason why I'm captain of my country: I've worked my bollocks off to get where I am, and by doing that, I've been able to make the most of whatever talent I have."<ref name=tribune/>

[[Fábio Aurélio]], a predecessor Liverpool left-back, in June 2020 said of Robertson: "He's kind of the complete player because physically he's well capable of going forward and going back he defends very well." He added, "He's quick, so his one-v-one is good", and "he's always improving, he's not comfortable in his situation being first choice."<ref name=legliv>{{Cite web|url=https://legacy.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/397907-the-complete-player-fabio-aurelio-assessment-of-andy-robertson|title='The complete player' – Fabio Aurelio's assessment of Andy Robertson|date=10 June 2020|website=Liverpool FC}}</ref>

== Philanthropy ==
In March 2018 Robertson donated a Liverpool shirt signed by teammate [[Roberto Firmino]], to a young boy who had given his pocket money to a local [[food bank]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/43324198 |title=Andrew Robertson gifts Liverpool top to young fan for making foodbank donation |website=BBC Sport |date=8 March 2018 |access-date=9 March 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' reported in March 2020 that Robertson had donated significant sums to food banks in the Glasgow area.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/sport/liverpools-andy-robertson-believed-to-be-player-behind-huge-foodbank-donation-in-scotland-hvzfmrjpb |title=Liverpool's Andy Robertson believed to be player behind huge foodbank donation in Scotland |newspaper=The Sunday Times |first=Jonathan |last=Northcroft |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> In November 2020, Robertson founded the AR26 Charity, which aims to help socially deprived and critically-ill children.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Liverpool and Scotland defender Andy Robertson launches charity to help young people |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/12143091/liverpool-and-scotland-defender-andy-robertson-launches-charity-to-help-young-people |access-date=27 April 2024 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref>

In September 2020, Robertson released his first memoir, ''Robbo: Now You're Gonna Believe Us'', which mainly focuses on Liverpool's [[2019–20 Liverpool F.C. season|2019–20 campaign]]. All proceeds from the book go to Robertson's foundation, which helps underprivileged children in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hunter |first=Andy |title=Andy Robertson relishing 'fun' of proving Liverpool's doubters wrong |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/sep/18/andy-robertson-relishing-fun-of-proving-liverpools-doubters-wrong |date=18 September 2020 |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited |access-date=23 November 2020}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Robertson married Rachel Roberts in the summer of 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liverpool "squad goals" photo from Andy Robertson's wedding goes viral |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2022/07/liverpool-squad-goals-photo-from-andy-robertsons-wedding-goes-viral/ |last=Lusby |first=Jack |date=18 July 2022 |website=This Is Anfield |access-date=19 July 2022}}</ref> The couple have three children, a son (born 2017) and two daughters (born 2019 & 2023).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/andy-robertson-reveals-liverpool-icon-11090277 |title=Andy Robertson reveals Liverpool icon Kenny Dalglish told him he's got his back |last=McDermott |first=Scott |date=1 September 2017 |newspaper=Daily Record |access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-victory-perfect-end-special-15672380 |title=Liverpool victory was perfect end to special week for Andy Robertson |last=Pearce |first=James |date=13 January 2019 |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |access-date=22 January 2019}}</ref> In 2019 he was reported living in [[Formby]].<ref name=guarob>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/may/30/andy-robertson-liverpool-champions-league-final-tottenham|title=Andy Robertson: 'We don't deserve anything yet. The league shows that'|first=Andy|last=Hunter|work=The Guardian|date=30 May 2019}}</ref> He is a practising [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://extra.ie/2020/09/19/sport/soccernews/liverpool-andy-robertson-sean-cox |title=Andy Robertson says meeting Sean Cox drove Liverpool to win Premier League |last=Arnold |first=Barry |date=19 September 2020 |newspaper=extra.ie |access-date=12 June 2021}}</ref>

Robertson was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[2023 New Year Honours]] for services to association football, charity and young people.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=63918|supp=y|page=N23|date=31 December 2022}}</ref><ref name = mbe>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/64126616 |title=New Year's Honours: Andy Robertson, Jen Beattie, Kim Little & Dave Ferguson get MBEs |website=BBC Sport |date=30 December 2022 |accessdate=31 December 2022}}</ref>

